issue(id="0012" status="open")
  title Enable direct mobile access to scrubs guests via Tailscale SSH
  user-story
    as-a scrubs user programming remotely from my phone
    i-want scrubs guests to be directly reachable over Tailscale with a phone-friendly SSH path
    so-that I can connect to a guest itself rather than depending on host-local Lima forwarding or a desktop intermediary
  premise.
    Scrubs guests currently expose SSH through host-local Lima port forwarding,
    with host aliases that resolve to `127.0.0.1` plus an instance-specific
    forwarded port. That model works well from the Mac host, but it does not
    produce a true phone-to-guest access path because the guest is not directly
    reachable from the phone and password SSH is intentionally disabled.

    The desired product direction is direct remote reachability without exposing
    guest services or Codex app-server listeners on the public internet. A
    mesh-network path is the better fit. Tailscale is the immediate candidate,
    and the preferred auth model for this task is Tailscale SSH rather than
    guest passwords or ordinary LAN-exposed SSH listeners.

    The implementation should treat Tailscale as clean guest infrastructure:
    installed and managed in NixOS guest configuration, not smuggled through
    the dirty `mise` runtime. The design must preserve the clean/dirty
    boundary, preserve existing host-side bootstrap and `limactl shell` flows,
    and avoid requiring a persistent real guest password purely to satisfy
    mobile access.
  acceptance-criteria
    criterion Scrubs has a documented, supported path to make a guest directly reachable from a phone over a tailnet rather than only through host-local `127.0.0.1` Lima forwarding.
    criterion The preferred remote auth path is Tailscale SSH, and the design does not require enabling real guest password authentication as the normal mobile-access path.
    criterion Guest-side Tailscale installation, state, and launch behavior live in clean guest configuration rather than the dirty `mise` runtime or other ambient dirty-space tooling.
    criterion At least one representative guest such as `wayforge` can be enrolled and reached directly from a phone-oriented workflow, with a concrete validation path for both direct SSH use and the intended Codex/ChatGPT mobile SSH-host flow if that client supports it.
    criterion Existing local scrubs workflows remain intact, including bootstrap, `limactl shell <instance>`, host-local SSH access, and the current clean-auth model for `gh` and Codex.
    criterion The resulting documentation explains the operator flow end to end: how a guest joins the tailnet, how its remote identity is discovered or named, how mobile access is initiated, and which client constraints still require compatibility checks.
    criterion The work explicitly documents the threat-model tradeoff of giving a guest first-class network identity and states what remains intentionally disallowed or unchanged.
  review-items
    item(status="open").
      Decide whether Tailscale support should live in scrubs base as an opt-in
      module, in project shims, or in a small clean-side stack that guests can
      compose without forcing every guest onto the tailnet.
    item(status="open").
      Decide how guest enrollment should happen during bootstrap versus after
      bootstrap, including whether scrubs should support host-provided auth
      keys, tagged ephemeral-style enrollment, or a manual `tailscale up`
      ceremony for now.
    item(status="open").
      Validate the actual mobile-client behavior for Tailscale SSH, especially
      whether the current phone-side SSH-host flow accepts keyless Tailscale
      SSH compatibility semantics or requires a different connection pattern.
    item(status="open").
      Decide whether guest hostnames should remain instance-derived, gain an
      explicit stable tailnet naming convention, or support both.
